Vaccines received in series on 12/11/20 and 1/11/21. Three days before due date for second COVID vaccine, started severely itching and experiencing hive-like rash all over body, especially to hands and head; mostly relieved by benadryl but wore off every 6 hours. Contacted PCP (listed in form) who suggested taking zyrtec and using a moisturizing lotion. This helped for the day of receiving the vaccine. Thinking it was something unrelated due to the time elapsed from the vaccine, despite no changes in consumption or products/environment encountered, I went ahead and got the second vaccine. Day 1 after vaccine, I experienced the usually reported side effects, including slightly elevated temp, chills, and body aches. Itching and hives continued but not as noticeable due to other side effects. The next morning, hives and itching were significantly worse; any time I scratched (or something touched my skin more than lightly), large, red welps would nearly immediately develop, and often had raised bumps within the irritations. To date, this is continued, slightly relieved by allergy medications, but not entirely and must be taken around the clock or severe symptoms will begin again.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I felt very heavy (especially my limbs) and had a slight headache on Thursday (the day after receiving the vaccine). I felt dizzy and slow moving for the next several hours.  My blood pressure was rated as normal, blood oxygen normal, and pulse slightly low by a nurse on staff who took my vitals after the episode.   My temperature, which had been 97.8 prior to the event that morning (typical for me) was elevated during this time to 100.2 and returned to normal after approximately 4 hours without medication.  I was fatigued, so I slept for approximately 4-5 hours that afternoon and began feeling better the following day (Saturday).

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I received 2nd injection of Pfizer COVID-19 Vaccine at 1015AM on 1-12-21 and was doing great. I had taken one 325mg Tylenol and one  200mg Ibuprofen approximately 60 minutes prior to receiving vaccine (which is what I did prior to the first vaccine). I was doing great initially following the vaccine. I took another 325mg Tylenol and 200mg Ibuprofen when I went to bed at 2000  1-12-21. At 0300 1-13-21 I woke up feeling nauseated and when attempting to turn over to my right side I moaned loudly because I could not hardly move my left arm. My husband was woken and turned on the bedroom light and we noted a 3 inch bruise and large knot on my left deltoid at the injection site. He told me that I felt warm. I took my temperature that was 101.2 degrees. I took 650mg Tylenol and that time. At 0500 1-13-21 I was having chills, muscle and joint aches. I could not fully close my hands into a grip. My "brain" hurt, not a headache but literally it hurt to move my head. I would occasionally get a sharp pain in the front and back of my head. My temperature went to its highest at approximately 1500 1-13-21 to 102.5 degrees. I continued to offset Tylenol with Ibuprofen throughout the day. At 2000 1-13-21 my temperature was 101.8 and began to trend downward.  I went to bed and when I woke up on 1-14-21 I felt 100% better with just a little fatigue from the inability to sleep the day prior.
OTHER_MEDS: Synthroid 125 mcg daily; Lexapro 20mg daily; Adderall 20mg BID;OTC Allegra seasonal allergies:

Vaccine was administered to patient in his room at 12:50pm.  After the patient finished his lunch in his room he was wheeled out to the nursing station for observation.  at 1:30pm the nurse wheeled patient into our working/set up area and stated that patient is having a vaccine reaction.  I observed that his lips were noticeably swollen.  I asked patient to stick out his tongue, it also was noticeably swollen.  Only the tip of his tongue extended about 1/2 inch past his lips.  I administered 0.3mg of Epinephrine via and epi-pen into his right thigh and instructed the nursing staff to call 911.  Patient improved markedly over the next 10 minutes when Fire Department EMT's arrived.  Nursing staff monitored his  blood pressure, heart rate and pulse  and oxygen sat.  heart rate was elevated somewhat likely due to epi , BP was 121/73, pulse steady and ox sat good.  Fire Department transported patient to a nearby ER for further evaluation and treatment if necessary.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Maybe 1 minute after receiving the vaccine I began to have a syncopal episode, the nurse practitioner thought that since I was heavy I began to have a vasovagal reaction.  From there they asked me to sit with the others waiting 15 minutes to make sure they were ok to leave. As I sat the symptoms would come and go, as if in a pattern, and then return.  The longer I sat there the more the symptoms began to grow, after sitting for an hour they decided to send me to the ER. At this time I was experiencing nausea, vomiting, sweating, I was itchy, I could not stop coughing, it was difficult to breath, and I had the worse headache.  When I got to the ER they gave me drugs to reverse the allergic reaction and told me they would watch me for a while. In the next 4 hours all of the symptoms started again and I had to get another round of the reaction drugs, I ended up going through this process 4 times before I was safe enough to go home the next day.  The provider that saw me and admitted me did not do any blood work or labs, they simply provided me with the reaction drugs when needed and my home medications.

Relevant medical history, past medical treatment, vaccination details and family history were not provided.  Concomitant medications included MEASLES VACCINE LIVE (ENDERS-EDMONSTON), MUMPS VACCINE LIVE (JERYL LYNN), RUBELLA VACCINE LIVE (WISTAR RA 27/3), VARICELLA ZOSTER VACCINE LIVE (OKA/MERCK) (PROQUAD) and PNEUMOCOCCAL VACCINE CONJ 7V (CRM197) (PREVNAR). Reporter stated the system would allow it to be entered another way as a single product, but it was more difficult to enter it that way in the system. SYMPTOM_TEXT: About 2 min after receiving injection, I felt an intense flushing feeling all over, it felt as if my blood had turned into lava. About a minute after that I felt a "tickle" in my throat. The same sensation I felt  when I had my reaction to Gadolinium.  I tried to swallow, and it was a little difficult. I did NOT feel short of breath. I tried to calm down by doing slow concentrated breathing. I continued to take small sips of water to gauge my swallowing ability. After about 2-3 minutes, the flushing sensation subsided, and swallowing started to improve.  I had brought my Epinephrine pen with me.  About 1-2 min after the flushing sensation had subsided,, it came back and my swallowing ability got much worse, to the point I couldn't  swallow a small sip. I was breathing well, and did NOT feel short of breath, but gave myself my Epinephrine injection at that time. A Rapid Response was called at that time, my vitals signs taken, an IV inserted, 911 called. O2 sats were fine mid 90's, heart rate was mid 80's, BP was elevated,  I don't remember the exact systolic 170-180, but my diastolic was 116. It took the ambulance approximately 10-15 min to arrive. By the time the ambulance arrived, I was feeling close to my baseline and my BP was improving.  I was seen by the ER MD, and feeling fairly well, my throat still felt a tiny bit tight, but no difficulties swallowing.  The plan was to complete  treatment with IV steroids, Benadryl, and Pepcid, then be observed for a few more hours. This was approximately around 16:30. Not more than 5 min after MD left my room, I got the flushing feeling, and throat closing feeling again. While the medications were being prepared these  symptoms increased, ( I could still breath adequately and vital signs were still  OK.  It took about 10 minutes after meds were given for symptoms to begin to subside ( No epi given) I was observed until 21:30 then discharged. I am taking 50 mg daily x 3 days, 25mg Benadryl q 8hrs x 3 days, and 20mg Pepcid bid x 3 days. I feel fine , no further episodes

Patient developed angioedema of her eyelids after COVID-19 vaccination.  She received her Covid vaccine on 1/10/2021 at 11:30 AM.  She received the Pfizer vaccine.  She works at a nursing home.  She had some fatigue and tiredness during the day but woke up on the second day without any symptoms.  On 1/30/2021, she developed bilateral eyelid swelling.  The swelling is mild to moderate intensity involving the upper and lower eyelids bilaterally with a prickly burning sensation associated with pruritus.  The reaction lasted less than a day and resolved without any skin desquamation, scarring or bruising.  She denies any hives anywhere else.  She does not have a large local reaction at the injection site.  She denies respiratory complaints, GI symptoms, lightheadedness, loss of consciousness, wheezing, swelling of her throat or other symptoms consistent with anaphylaxis.  She used Benadryl with significant improvement.   She had a significant reaction after influenza vaccination consisting of swelling of her face and her eyelids with development of dry patches bilaterally within 2 days, resolving with skin desquamation.  The reaction lasted for 1 week.  She received her influenza vaccination in October 20, 2020.   She was seen in our office in 2012 for bilateral eyelid angioedema with associated urticaria shortly after swimming in the pool.  She was given oral antihistamines ?Zyrtec once daily? with significant improvement as well as prevention of this reaction.  She has not had this reaction  for more than 6 years.
HISTORY: History of hives and eyelid angioedema  afterswimming in pools in 2012, improving on cetirizine 10mg 1 pill daily

Vaccine administered around 5:30pm Thursday, January 7th. Severe site pain within the first few hours of receiving vaccine, lasting about 48 straight hours. Within 8 hours of receiving the vaccine, my entire body began to ache and by the next morning I could hardly get out of bed due to the pain in my muscles. They felt like they had tightened or seized up. I could not take a step without wincing. Body chills came next, though I was unable to get out of bed to get my  thermometer from the bathroom. By Saturday morning, I had more range of motion in my extremities, but it was not until Sunday evening that I could lift my left arm (the one the received the inoculation) over my head. There was a red, circular non-irritating rash surrounding the site of injection for 5 days following injection. I have no allergies to any medications, but did test positive for the Covid virus on March 18th, 2020. I realize my body's reaction was a normal physiologic response to the antibodies my body created within the last 9 months, however I am an otherwise healthy 34 year old female and wanted to report my experience because I could not find evidence that anyone else has had the same experience following the first dose of the covid vaccine.

I then proceeded to vaccinate patient after she verified and verbalized authorization to administer. I then did the same process with husband.  After receiving vaccination, patient was escorted to the observation room for 15 minute waiting period to be monitored for any reactions. After patient sat down with husband who was also vaccination I verified they felt fine and reiterated the importance of notification of any side effects to monitor for, pointed them to the medics in the room and both patient and husband verbalized understanding. A conversation of signing up mom and other family  members to receive vaccine through our notification system online was also talked about for an additional 2-3 minutes and then I said my goodbye, thanked them, and left the observation room. I received Moderna vaccine on 01/06/2021. Normal pain at the injection site occured with little concern. Pain in armpit began 01/08/2021. I did not think anything of it, believing the pain to be from an ingrown hair caused by shaving or just something with the vaccine. I ignored it to spend time with family. On 01/12/2021 I noticed the pain had not subsided and deepened into the armpit causing pain to radiate from the area when lifting or moving heavy items.  I palpated the area and felt a pea sized lump. It moved freely. I could not locate it again. I continued to palpate into the top of my shoulder and discovered a large lump in the clavicle area. It is painful to apply pressure. I knew these areas to be part of the lymphatic system. I also did research on side effects of the Moderna vaccine but observed most people to have lymph node symptoms for only 24-48 hours within three days of receiving the vaccine then they subside.  I made an appointment that same day, 01/12/2021, with Dr. at clinic to be examined. At first, Dr was dismissive of my symptoms. Dr did physically examine my areas of complaint and scheduled an ultrasound for 01/15/2021 at  Hospital. On 01/13/2021 I noticed the injection site began to ache again. On 01/14/2021 I awoke from a nap at 6pm. I began showering for work when I felt a burning, itchy sensation on my inner left bicep. I observed two red spots on my inner left bicep close to my armpit with a red rash below the two red spots. I palpated the red spots to find a large and slightly smaller lump under the skin corresponding with the red spots. The rash itches. As of 01/15/2021, the ultrasound had to be rescheduled by the hospital as their ultrasound technician cannot make it into work because of a blizzard. I now have two lumps in the clavicle area that alternate swelling and reducing in size. I've been taking tylenol every four hours when I'm awake to control the pain. The ones in my clavicle now cause tension in the left side of my neck. I've also applied warm compresses on the affected sites. It helps lessen the swelling for a bit but does come back.
Red, swollen, warm area at the site of injection 7 days after vaccine.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I was awoken from sleep with violent chills and an sensation of severe cold. My chills became violent and coarse rigors, severe enough to contract the spine into hyperextension if I kept my body in a neutral position. I could still activate each muscle group to keep in a fetal prostration pose. I was knowledgeable of the event, did not loose any bowel, bladder, or smooth muscle function, and the intensity of the rigors was focused on the most developed skeletal muscles (thighs, calves, upper arms, forearms, paraspinal muscles, hands, respectively).  Jaw and muscles of the head/face seemed unaffected. Fingers and toes not distinctly affected. I was not sweating at this time and there were NO other symptoms to report; I remained lucid and able to self-reflect the entire time. Home temperature is kept to consistent 66F, no malfunctions to thermostat. No recent changes to bedding (sheet and quit on top of mattress); it is even optimized for me as I tend to overheat as I sleep.   At 50 minutes, I felt "less frozen" and confident enough to stand/ambulate for 220mg naproxen + 500mg APAP , cautiously and successfully swallowed. Robe was donned over existing pajamas and thick comforter was pulled from hallway closet. Rigors continued, but it appeared that intentional activation of the muscle groups could still overpower the rigors for safe (but shaky) ambulation. Greatest risk was coarsely shaking hands a bringing cup to mouth to swallow pills.   Above activity was completed in 5 minutes. I then sat upright in bed under layers above. I could feel the muscles calm and relax, with episode completely ending in 5 minutes. Total time of event: 60 minutes.   Post-event details: There was a mild sensation of muscle tension in the posterior cervical spine akin to whiplash, but no residual symptoms. I debriefed with my husband shortly thereafter (he has been in another room the whole time) and fell asleep by 23:30. Awoke to alarm at 05:00 and able to stretch, accomplish 30 min run, vacuum/mop the floors, and present to work by 08:00am without deficit.  Time of documentation: 11:22 am 1/15/2021
HISTORY: hyperreactive airway triggered by inspiration of dustmite feces and smoking. No hospitalizations, condition is managed by meditation, breathing pattern therapy, sleep, and prophylactic management to reduce allergens in home.
ALLERGIES: No known allergies to ingestible products as an adult. VERY slight hypersensitivity to large amounts of tropical fruit as a child. Last reaction >15 years ago.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 1/13/21 0740 Received second dose of COVID-19 vaccine, which was scheduled for that morning. Did not experience anaphylaxis or other symptoms of vaccine injury. I took 1gram of Tylenol PO when I got back to my motel by 0830.  By 0924 I noted that my left deltoid (injection site) and arm were very sore/achy. I fell asleep until 1740. I noted that I was experiencing more body aches at this time (joint and muscle, especially in my bilateral shoulders, lower back, knees and pelvis). Calf muscles were quite sore. I made pasta with red sauce and made a pot of blueberry tea, ate and went back to bed. 2327 I woke again with weird fever dreams and my right bicep was intermittently twitching. I think I was starting to run a low grade fever at this time (my ears felt hot, and my stomach was queasy but was not nauseous), no diaphoresis, shortness of breath or airway constriction. I remained awake until 0200, 1/14/21. By 0400 I was experiencing mild chills, face was flushed, headache on the right, with pressure behind my right eye, parietal and occipital areas of my skull. The pain extended into the right muscles of my neck (trapezius, levator scapulae and sternocleidomastoid muscles). Bilateral upper arm muscles and joints were 5:10 pain. I was also experiencing mild photophobia, but not migraine related, and a mild non-productive cough and pressure behind my facial and ethmoid sinuses with scant viscous secretions at the back of my throat. 0433 I forced myself to get out of bed and head to the bathroom. My temp was 101. I took a very hot shower and am back in bed. Experiencing a lot of malaise and lethargy. 1/15/21 0830 temp is currently 99.1, headache is present, 3:10. Joint aches have mostly subsided. Injection site is warm and tender, but no erythema is present.
OTHER_MEDS: Vitamin C, D, B complex, red rice yeast extract

The unexpected reaction was localized constant left chest pain. It is believed to be due to swollen lymph nodes in the pectoral area (as all other testing at the ER was normal). Also sharp pain when breathing in deeply.
LAB_DATA: "Within few hours Dizziness Slight nausea Slight shakiness  Within 4 hours Increased fatigue* Headache* Mild body aches* Slight nausea/ dizziness* Mild GI symptoms  Took tylonel regularly after this point  Within 18 hours Continued * symptoms increasing in severity Body chills Fever noted periodically when tylonel wearing off (never went above 102) Chest pain- constant, achy, left side (always more painful than arm)/Sharp pain when breathing in deeply Moderate arm soreness (side of injection)  Trouble sleeping due to all these symptoms, especially the chest pain Called doctor in AM (next day, tue) about chest pain. She was unavailable.   Things seemed to get worse for the next 30 or so hours. At some point I started alternating ibuprofen and tylonel in an attempt to get more relief as I was worried I was taking too much tylonel (as per the label). Was in bed only getting up for water/br. After that, the symptoms seemed to start to get better but the chest pain remained constant. I also noticed mild to moderate joint pain when the other symptoms decreased enough that I actually got out of bed.  Call back from doctor's nurse about 48 hours after shot (Wednesday afternoon): she was concerned why I didn't go to ER for chest pain, and recommended I at least go to urgent care just to make sure.  Went to ER at about 5PM (Wednesday) EKG good, chest x-ray clear, covid test negative, blood work good (no cardiac event evidence, slightly low white blood cells, d-dimer elevated possible to vaccination response itself?), lungs clear- CT with contrast.  The doctor was not sure what it was other than an unexplained side effect of the vaccination... until we did the CT (which was done last) and she seemed somewhat surprised to find swollen lymph nodes all in the left pectoral area. She believes this is a reaction to the vaccination. Both my doctor's office and the ER doctor didn't know of other people noting chest pain like I had after the vaccination. We were both happy and relieved to have an answer. Should go away on its own within a few weeks. Recommended to follow up with primary care in a few weeks to make sure the swelling goes away.  So, I experienced all of the possible side effects listed. What is not listed is chest pain and the (likely associated) sharp pain when breathing in deeply. That was my reason for calling the doctor. The other side effects I was at least prepared for. When the chest pain did not decrease like the rest of the side effects I figured it was better to be safe than sorry.  Wednesday night I slept much better and only recorded a slightly elevated temperature when tylonel wearing off (99.7). Still have that left side chest pain but feel much better knowing what it is. Also, a little tired, bit of a headache, dizziness and left arm pain. "

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Wednesday 1/13/2021 I woke up feeling like nauseous, then later in the day I started to get itchy in my lower body that was coming and going (I believe I still had some allegra d in my system). On  Thursday 01/14/2021 by noon time the itching had become extreme and unbearable all over my body and felt like my skin was crawling/burning, my chest and parts of my arms were really red . I also developed a lump in my throat that kept getting bigger and felt itchy and couldn't stop clearing my throat. Around 3pm I took 10ml of Claritin. The Claritin had not really helped however the redness had gone down a lot and by 4:30 I was miserable. Informed by a provider I work with to go to urgent care. I arrived at urgent care at about 5:10 where I was treated for an allergy reaction. I was given  0.9% sodium chloride IV bolus 500mL, Methylprednisolone sod suc(PF) (SOLU-Medrol) 125mg Intravenous, Famotidine (Pepcid) 20mg/2ml injection 20mg intravenous, diphenhydramine (Benadryl) 50mg/ml injection 25mg intravenous.  The itching subsided within 30 minutes, the itchy throat/ lump was still present but was not getting worse and slowly improving.   I was discharged home and was told to pick up famotidine 20mg, otc benadryl and prednisone 50mg to take for 5 days.  got home a little after 7 and was able to eat dinner, let dog out, shower, rest  before going to bed. I did take another 10 ml of Benadryl at 10:30. Woke up without any itchy skin at 5:45 and was able to return to work this morning. I still have a slight itchy throat but it is tolerable. I took allegra d and famotidine this morning. I am holding off on the prednisone because of the immune response to vaccines from steroids. I don't want to lessen the effectiveness of the vaccine.
OTHER_MEDS: Adderall 30mg XR, junel 1.5/30 (21) 1.5-30 mg-mcg tablet, Flonase 50mcg nasal spray,  had allegra d in my system-last dose taken was Monday.
HISTORY: endometriosis, environmental allergies, contact dermatitis due to allergies, kidney stones, ADHD, migraines,
ALLERGIES: sensitivities to penicillin and flagyl, nickel, environmental

SYMPTOM_TEXT: My reaction occurred approximately 12 hrs. following the injection.  I awoke on the night of Jan. 8 after rolling over on my right arm where the injection site was.   I immediately awakened with sharp burning pain and as I became more awake, I realized that I was confused, slightly disoriented and very diapheretic.  I alternated between having a chill to sweating profusely.  My head was throbbing as in a migraine and the orbits around my eyes hurt as well.  I was extremely nausea to the point of gagging but I had not eaten anything so I did not throw up.  Later that night I also at watery diarrhea.  All of my joints ached and my pelvic region seemed to hurt more than the rest of my body and joints.  When I got up, I found that my equilibrium was off and that I was dizzy. My temperature 100.2 but over the next 2 days it went as high as 102, but continued around 100.8 for several hours.  Early in the a.m. I called my PCP service and later spoke with the physician on call.  We discussed in depth.  At that point, my panic had subsided somewhat and he told me to take Tylenol for my fever and I also had Benadryl available and I took 50 mg.  I hydrated myself (I did not have an appetite) but forced my to drink fluids and eat a serving of fresh fruit.  By mid-day on 1/9 I was feeling less anxious and was able to sit and watch t.v.  I continued to take Tylenol and Benadryl and slept for almost 16 hours.  On Sunday I was more improved.  Since then, I have continued to feel dizziness and tire very easily.  Today, my equilibrium is still off and I have difficulty focusing.  I have spoken with my PCP twice this week and I will be going into the Covid research clinic next week as they want to examine me and draw blood samples close to the two week period after the first injection.

Within 48 hours any soreness went away and I was fine until Wednesday, 1/13/2021 afternoon. My injection site had become itchy and slightly sore.  By that evening the site was quite sore, red and slightly swollen. The following morning the site had swollen to a soft ball size, was an angry red, extremely painful and warm to the touch. At noon it was still worsening so I called and made an appointment with my doctor.  I am now being treated for cellulitis (a deep tissue infection). I was prescribed Anti-biotics. I have yet to see any improvement, in fact the redness is still spreading.

I felt slightly warmer. I decided to wait the full 30 minutes. When I went to stand had a moment of dizziness that passed but then I felt lightheadedness for about 2 hours after the injection. My ear felt like it was warm and there was slight pressure there. My throat continued to feel irritated and still feels lightly irritated after 4 days.  After about 3 hours it felt like something lifted and I felt better. That night I was really fatigued and tired. Maybe slightly cold. The next day felt fine except for the throat irritation that still persists today.  The side where I received the injection my arm, shoulder, and chest area felt affected for two days after receiving injection.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Within 2-5 minutes of receiving the vaccine, I began to feel dizzy.  I signaled for help while in my car  and help arrived. Within the next few minutes the severity seemed to go from ?0-100? and I began to feel a deep impending sense of doom and panic/fear. I also felt extremely tense in my muscles and felt itchy in the chest area. That continued for 15 minutes or so before subsiding slowly. Staff surrounded my car and were very supportive and great about the situation.   It was one of the most frightening experiences to date I have had. No EpiPen type intervention was done. Once the event was on the downswing I was kept for additional observation and release on my own accord.  Everyone there was great. I am reporting for my own records in case further testing reveals I have an allergy to this vaccine for employment purposes should the vaccine become mandated prior to me having alternative means of vaccination or allergy testing competed to determine if it was an true reaction or not so I can get vaccinated safely.
LAB_DATA: None. The event peaked at about 15 minutes post injection and I was simply held for longer evaluation waiting time before being able to leave.  Vaccine site staff stayed with me the entire time and were great.  I now plan on asking for a referral to an allergist to get testing before I attempt vaccination at this time.  Doctor appointment will be in early February.
PRIOR_VAX: The whooping cough vaccine as a child
ALLERGIES: Penicillin Amoxicillin Ceclor  Sulfa  I also had a bad allergic reaction to the whooping cough vaccine as a child and have had to get a modified version ever since.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Gradual onset of soreness beginning about an hour post-vaccine and worsening throughout day. By the evening, left arm pain was too uncomfortable to wash dishes and lift household objects. Pain woke me up at 3am that night and I could not push the covers off of me, dress or undress, and I experienced severe pain with slight movement (7/10). Nausea and cold sweats began around 5am and lasted for 45min. I contacted the nurse via messaging system and was told to take OTC nausea medicine and Tylenol. I took the maximum dosage for Tylenol that day but could not do my normal school functions. The next day I was still limited by pain but did not require medication to cope. By day three, I had full range of motion back and minimal pain. Day four I am back to exercising normally.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Abdominal discomfort; Abdominal pain; Lightheaded/Dizzy; Having trouble taking deep breaths/couldn't breath; Sweating; Hyperventilating; Developed blotchy skin; Shaking; Headache; Vomited; A spontaneous report (United States) was received from a health care professional concerning a 50-year-old, female patient who received Moderna's COVID-19 vaccine and experienced abdominal discomfort, abdominal pain, lightheaded/dizzy, having trouble taking deep breaths/couldn't breathe, sweating, hyperventilating, developed blotchy skin, shaking, headache, and vomited.   The patient's medical history included current conditions of mild osteopenia, gastroesophageal reflux disease, anemia, and allergic reaction (anaphylaxis) to metoclopramide. Concomitant products known to have been used by the patient, within two weeks prior to the event, included cefixime, ibuprofen, omeprazole, estradiol, and hydrocodone bitartrate, paracetamol.     On 22 Dec 2020, the patient received their first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (Lot number: 011J20A) in their left arm for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection.   On 22 Dec 2020, the patient told a medical assistant in the waiting area that she felt ill to her stomach and she was having trouble taking deep breaths. The patient was found in a nearby bathroom sitting on the floor. She had vomited, reported she was lightheaded, couldn't breath, was shaking, had abdominal discomfort, and was sweating. It was attempted to move the patient to a wheelchair, but she did not respond well to the transfer. The patient reported the symptoms worsening: headache, abdominal pain, and developed blotch skin, hyperventilating, and was dizzy. A code blue was called and the patient was given a 0.5mg Epinephrine injection. The patient was sent to the emergency room. Treatment for the event included 0.5mg Epinepherine injection, famotidine, ondansetron HCl, prednisone 60mg, and lorazepam 1mg intravenously.   Action taken with mRNA-1273 in response to the events was not provided.  The events abdominal discomfort, abdominal pain, lightheaded/dizzy, having trouble taking deep breaths/couldn't breathe, sweating, hyperventilating, developed blotchy skin, shaking, headache, and vomited were considered not resolved.; Reporter's Comments: This case concerns a 50 year old female patient with medical history of mild osteopenia, gastroesophageal reflux disease, anemia, and allergic reaction (anaphylaxis) to metoclopramide, who experienced events of Abdominal discomfort, Abdominal pain, Dizziness, Dyspnoea, Hyperhidrosis, Hyperventilation, Rash macular, Tremor, Headache, and Vomiting following their first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (Lot number: 011J20A). The patient was found ill in the waiting room after leaving clinic prior to completing 15 minute observation time. Very limited information regarding the events has been provided at this time. Based on temporal association between the use of the product and the onset of the events, a causal relationship cannot be excluded.
OTHER_MEDS: FLEXERIL [CEFIXIME]; ADVIL 12 HOUR; PROTONIX [OMEPRAZOLE]; ESTRACE; VIVELLE DOT; NORCO
HISTORY: Medical History/Concurrent Conditions: Anemia; GERD; Osteopenia

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Like an anaphylactic reaction; Tested positive for Covid 19; A spontaneous report was received from a pharmacist concerning a female patient who received Moderna's COVID-19 Vaccine (mRNA-1273) experienced the events, tested positive for COVID-19 and like an anaphylactic reaction.  The patient's medical history was not provided. No relevant concomitant medications were reported.   On an unknown date, approximately one day prior to the onset of the events, the patient received their first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 intramuscularly for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection.  On an unknown date, the next day following vaccine administration, the patient began to experience increased pulse, acceleration in her heart beat, difficulty breathing, and other symptoms like an anaphylactic reaction. The patient also tested positive for COVID-19, although she was asymptomatic prior to receiving the mRNA-1273 vaccine. Treatment for the event included intramuscular Benadryl.   Action taken with mRNA-1273 in response to the events was not reported.  The events, tested positive for COVID-19 and like an anaphylactic reaction, were unknown.; Reporter's Comments: This case concerns a female patient with unknown medical history, who received their first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (Lot unknown),  and who experienced the serious unlisted event of Anaphylactic reaction and the non-serious unlisted event of SARS-CoV-2 test positive. Very limited information regarding this event of anaphylactic reaction has been provided at this time.  Based on improvement of symptoms after treatment with Benadryl and temporal association between the use of the product and the start date of the event on the day following vaccination, a causal relationship cannot be excluded making the event of anaphylactic reaction possibly related to the vaccine.  Based on the latency of infection with SARS-CoV-2 prior to testing positive for the virus, the temporal association between the use of the product and the start date of the event tested positive for COVID-19 on the day following vaccination, the event is assessed as unlikely related to mRNA-1273.

fever; body aches; severe nausea; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable healthcare professional reporting for self.  A 45-years-old female patient received BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 MRNA VACCINE), via an unspecified route of administration on 02Jan2021 at 12:00 PM (Dose 1) as a single dose in the left arm  (age at vaccination: 45 years old) for COVID-19 immunization. SYMPTOM_TEXT: almost like a thrush in her mouth, white tongue/ believes she had thrush; almost like a thrush in her mouth, white tongue; felt a little cold; legs were sore; headache; Sore arms; severe sore throats; back ache; low grade temp/Low grade fever; coughing; body aches/ whole body was achy; it was sore to swallow; lethargy; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable consumer reporting for self.  A 64-years-old female patient received BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 MRNA VACCINE), Batch/lot number: EL1284, Expiry Apr2021, intramuscularly on 30Dec2020 02:15 (Dose 1), right arm as a single dose (age at vaccination 64 years old) for COVID-19 immunization.  Medical history included allergy (usually in the fall she has allergy problems).  Her age is considered high risk, works in medical profession (Surgical Tech). Concomitant medication included levocetirizine (Walgreen's generic) 5mg, tablet, by mouth, at night for allergy. The patient had the first dose of the vaccine last 30Dec(2020) and after 2 days (on 01Jan2021) she developed symptoms: Sore arms, severe sore throats, back ache/ back was sore, temperature was up / low grade temp (never high), coughing, body aches. Her back and her legs were sore. Her whole body was achy. It was "like flu-ish kinda." She also had a headache. She started getting the sore throat and headache on 01Jan2021, and she felt a little cold on 02Jan2021. On 02Jan(2021), her first temperature was 100.5 degrees Fahrenheit. She states she had everything except for the GI issues. Around 02Jan(2021) or 03Jan(2021), her symptoms were progressively getting worse. She was told to get COVID tested. There were three exposures since Christmas Eve. So, she went and got a rapid COVID test (04Jan2021) and it came back negative. They also sent out a test that day. She was also tested for Strep (04Jan2021) too because her throat was so sore. It was almost like she had like thrush along with it. She states it was almost like a thrush because she had like a white tongue (onset 03Jan2021). Her throat was so sore, but it was a different kind of sore throat compared to a sore throat she has had before. She explains where the nasopharynx was at the top, it's almost like it was sore from there. It was sore to swallow, it was "a bizarre sore throat." She clarified she noticed the "thrushy" part of her throat around 03Jan2021. The strep test ended up being negative but she believes she had thrush because she was given medication and the medication was clearing that up. However, she still had the symptoms. Because her symptoms only started a few days before, they thought she should maybe wait a couple of days and if she is not feeling any better, she should be retested (for COVID). She went back again yesterday (07Jan2021). She had another Rapid COVID test and also a flu swab and both tests came back negative. She mentions they also did another COVID test (the send out type) and she should get that back around 1pm to find out the results of that.  They also did a CBC (07Jan2021) and everything was normal. Her white count was at 7. She was waiting for the 3rd COVID test result today (08Jan2021).  She reported that about three days afterwards, she didn't notice the soreness in /her arm. Her throat has improved. Her fever was down to 98 degrees Fahrenheit yesterday (07Jan2021). She states she was feeling better today (08Jan2021). She commented "the lethargy, though." She emptied the dishwasher yesterday (07Jan2021) and had to sit down after emptying it. She states her symptoms have her a little worried. She recovered from the sore arms in Jan2021. SYMPTOM_TEXT: more stiffness at the vaccination site; tiredness/fatigue; slight bleeding after the injection; when lifting my left arm/It felt heavier; pain at the time of syringe injection; This is a spontaneous report from a non-contactable consumer (patient). A male patient of an unspecified age received 2nd dose of BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE), via an unspecified route of administration in the left arm on 06Jan2021 13:30 at a single dose for COVID-19 immunization. The patient's medical history and concomitant medications were not reported. The patient previously received 1st dose of BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE) on 16Dec2020 for COVID-19 immunization and experienced vaccination site pain, vaccination site stiffness and  vaccination site movement impairment. The patient completed the second administration and had finalized his vaccination process. At first vaccine administration the patient mentioned it was no different from regular influenza vaccine. There was no special side effect. The patient woke up in the morning and there was pain at the time of syringe injection the same as 1st administration but there wasn't much feeling of the syringe being injected. After the administration, the patient was watched for around 30 minutes, but had no specific allergic reaction, just like the 1st administration. When he woke up this morning, and also in the evening of the vaccination day, although it is not sure if it is due to the vaccine, the patient had tiredness. His wife and child checked body temperature and pulse every 30 minutes. At the time of report, the patient woke up slightly early, but anyhow the difference was feeling of tiredness. Also there was more stiffness at the vaccination site that was felt more strongly than at 1st vaccination, especially when lifting left arm compared to the first vaccination. It felt heavier and sorer. The patient is feeling better and without any pain now. When talked about the second vaccination that he received, the patient look as though he was in pain when receiving it and reporter replied yes, slightly. At 1st administration there was no bleeding after the injection. But at 2nd administration there was slight bleeding after the injection so the patient was surprised. In summary, the patient had pain at injection with the syringe at 2nd administration,when the syringe was injected and also had pain a little after the injection, other than that, he had no special side effect. Outcome of the events was recovering.  No follow-up attempts are possible; information about lot/batch number cannot be obtained. No further information is expected.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I had no side effects after my vaccine on 12/24/20 until 1/8/21. On Friday, 1/8/21 at 830pm I began with severe abdominal pain, low grade fever, nausea and loss of appetite. My abdominal pain persisted and worsened over the next 24-36hours. I presented to the ER on Sunday, January 10, 2021 at 8am with severe right lower quadrant pain, pelvic pain, nausea and low grade fever. I was promptly diagnosed with appendicitis and taken to the OR at approximately 2pm on the same day.  In the OR my appendix was gangrenous, there was pus in the pelvic area nd fluid in my peritoneum. My appendix was not ruptured. My appendix was removed as well as part of the omentum. I remained in the hospital on IV Metronidazole and Ciprofloxacin for 2 days and was discharged on 1/13/21 at 9pm. I am continuing to recvoer at home on the same 2 antibiotics in oral form. I have a JP drain that is still in place. Of note I had two negative COVID 19 tests on 1/9/21 and 1/10/21. Both were PCR tests.
LAB_DATA: All of my medical workup was done at Hospital. On admission I had a CBC, CMP, Tropinin, CT of the abdomen and pelvis, CXR, Type and Cross, PT/PTT done. Of note my WBC was elevated to 13 and my CT was abnormal revealing appendicitis. My cultures and pathology intraoperatively have been negative.
HISTORY: Thyroidectomy 2/14, now on replacement therapy Overweight

30 y.o. female who was seen at SVH COVID Vaccine Clinic today for her first dose of the COVID 19 vaccination.    She denied any history of previous adverse reactions to vaccines.   She was given the Moderna vaccination in the left deltoid muscle.   During her 15 minute waiting period after the injection, the patient began to experience Right arm pain, numbness/tingling and soreness, note that injection was given in left arm.  She denied rash, hives, welts, difficulty breathing, difficulty swallowing, wheezing, throat tightness, hoarseness, stridor, itching, lightheadedness, dizziness, facial swelling, lip swelling and tongue swelling.   This provider was notified of patient reaction and she was then assessed in the emergency bay area.   Monitored patient for severe reaction symptoms, including but not limited to abdominal pain, blood pressure abnormality , chest pain, collapse, drooling, hypotension, increased swelling, rapid progression of symptoms, respiratory distress, skin changes, tongue swelling and vomiting.     ALLERGY REVIEW OF SYSTEMS:  Patient complains of muscle aches (Right arm)         Previous Reactions: No previous reactions to vaccines.     Objective    Vitals Vitals:   01/15/21 1239 01/15/21 1248 BP: 137/89 134/89 Pulse: 99 100 SpO2: 100% 100%     Blood Sugar 66 collected at 1236 * Patient given snack (granola bar) just before blood glucose checked.      Physical Exam Constitutional:      General: She is not in acute distress.    Appearance: Normal appearance. She is not ill-appearing.  Cardiovascular:     Rate and Rhythm: Normal rate.  Pulmonary:     Effort: Pulmonary effort is normal. No respiratory distress.  Musculoskeletal:     Right shoulder: She exhibits pain. She exhibits normal range of motion and no tenderness.     Right elbow: She exhibits normal range of motion and no swelling. No tenderness found.     Right wrist: She exhibits normal range of motion and no tenderness.  Skin:    General: Skin is warm and dry.  Neurological:     Mental Status: She is alert and oriented to person, place, and time.        Assessment/Plan  Treatment included: Ibuprofen/analgesics. Follow up response to treatment: no change. Patient discharge: Stable to go home and follow up with PCP.   Reports that she had work up for Guillain Barre 2.5 years ago but this was ruled out. States that she has had intermittent pain of all extremities since that time and has a handicap parking placard due to this. She denies any pain in right arm prior to the vaccine but states it started just a few minutes after administration. She has full ROM without difficulty and full sensation but reports some numbness and tingling as well as soreness but not necessarily tender to touch. Ibuprofen was administered but shortly after patient requesting to leave and feels this pain is the same as what she's had over the past 2.5 years but wanted to keep us aware. She will be discharging home and states she does not live alone.
Significant arm pain that has persisted since immunization, weakness and pain. Patient has tried oral corticosteroids, considering cortisone injection.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I received the vaccine around 10:40 am on January 8th, 2021. My arm was a little sore that night, but nothing too bad. I took some ibuprofen before I went to bed (400mg, I think). I felt fine the morning of January 9th; I went and bought some groceries and then took a walk in the neighborhood. I did get pretty chilled while walking since it was so cold. When I got back to my apartment around 2:00 I took a nap, then took a very hot shower trying to get warm again. Around 3:00 pm my arm started to become noticeably more sore so I took ibuprofen (600mg). Between 3:15 pm and 3:30 pm I suddenly started to feel warm and nauseous. I felt light-headed and while I was upright (standing or moving around) I would get some black spots in my vision. I went and lay down around 4:00 pm. I stayed in bed that whole evening with a fever (at its highest, 102), I was pretty nauseous, my arm hurt to the point where I couldn't move it and my wrist and hand felt very weak. I took some more ibuprofen (maybe another 600mg?) sometime after 8:00pm. The next day, Sunday January 10th, I mostly stayed in bed and ran a light fever (99.9) and was very fatigued. Arm was very sore and I had limited use of it until the latter part of the day. Monday, January 11th, I felt mostly fine, I could use my arm with no issue, but I stayed home from work due to the fatigue. By Tuesday I was fairly normal, just tired.
OTHER_MEDS: Loratadine 10mg (allergies) Latin 24 FE (birth control) Vitafusion Womens Gummy Vitamins mixed berry
ALLERGIES: Pet dander Hay fever Soy Aspirin (makes whites of eyes swell up)

We (myself and 2 other pharmacists) were conducting a COVID-19 vaccine clinic. The patient is on staff at the clinic and came in for her 1st dose of the Pfizer/BioNTech COVID vaccine. 10 minutes post-vaccination, patient started experiencing SOB, tingling fingers and face, and swelling of her lips and tongue. She moved herself outside to cooler air and then sent someone back inside to ask us for help. I ran outside with an EpiPen and immediately noted her pulse of 158 on her watch and she appeared to be experiencing an anaphylactic reaction. Patient stated she did not want to use the EpiPen but wanted to try chewing Benadryl instead first. I asked the staff for a blood pressure monitor and pulse oximeter. The 1st readings, approximately 12 minutes after vaccination, were HR 158, BP 155/105, and pulse ox 97%. Patient stated the Benadryl was working and her swelling was decreasing. The patient was not having trouble breathing at the time. I continued monitoring vitals and talking with the patient and approximately 20 minutes post-vaccination, she was improving (BP down to 134/80 and HR 120) but agreed we should call 911. She decided she wanted to move inside and lie down. I escorted her with support to a bed. Her vitals then increased again to BP 152/95 and HR 133 and her lips and tongue started swelling again. The patient appeared to be more labored in breathing then but still refused the EpiPen. Roughly 5 minutes after lying down, the medics showed up and took over and I went back to the vaccination area. I learned later that the patient refused to go to the hospital and after more observation was eventually allowed to leave with a friend/coworker driving her home.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient presented with history of anaphylaxis to shellfish. Nurse advised patient of need for 30 minute wait post covid 19 vaccine. Patient complied. After initial 30 minute wait, patient complained her mouth was dry and asked for water. Water provided, patient denied other symptoms. Based on history patient advised to wait another 20 minutes, and notify staff prior to leaving. 5-10 minutes later husband alerted nurse that she was feeling worse. Upon assessment, patient complained of swollen tongue, and difficulty swallowing. Adverse reaction protocol initiated. Client laid on cot, vitals taken, EMS called. Tourniquet applied above vaccination site, distal pulse check every 5 minutes. Nasal cannula, 4L applied. Blood pressure high, patient became flushed, complained of worsening in swallowing. Epi pen given in right thigh, Benadryl given IM in right deltoid. EMS arrived and took over care. Patient transported to hospital.
ALLERGIES: Codeine and Shellfish, and multiple ointment and creams.

I would go through phases where my body would get overwhelmed flushed and hot and I would be confused or dazed in that moment until it passed. I started to have vision problems in my right eye with it going blurry and pain behind my left eye almost as if it was swollen. SYMPTOM_TEXT: This facility staff member received her first dose of the MODERNA COVID-19 vaccine (Lot037K20A/EXP 6/22/21) at clinic at approximately 9:15AM on 1/14/21. She initially answered "no" to any allergies on the VAR but revealed to the pharmacist reviewing the VAR that she had experienced an allergy to food and contrast dye that required an epi-pen and hospital attention. She did not offer additional details and explained that she had tolerated other shots (including the 2020 flu shot) without incident. I advised patient to remain for a 30 minute monitoring period post-vaccination due to history of allergic reaction. Patient presented with some anxiety before the shot and immediately started to complain of feeling "sick" and said she was having trouble breathing due to chest pressure. We advised patient to remove her mask and provided her with water and a trash can though no vomiting occurred. After 15-20 minutes, patient still complained of chest pressure and difficulty breathing. When asked if she was experiencing any itchiness or throat swelling, patient said she did feel some throat swelling so she was given 25MG of Benadryl. After an additional 15 minutes, patient's condition seemed unchanged (not worsening, not improving) so the facility's nursing team was called to evaluate patient. Patient said she was still experiencing difficulty breathing and throat swelling so nursing advised use of EPI-PEN and patient consented. I administered a dose of 0.3MG (LOT0FM4066/EXP 02/2022) to the right lateral thigh and nurse called for EMS. Immediately after injection, patient's eyes fluttered and she seemed to be on the verge of fainting. Nursing checked her oxygen saturation which was 100%. Patient reported no improvement after 5 minutes so another EPI-PEN 0.3MG was administered to the left lateral thigh. Nursing also gave the patient 81MG chewable aspirin due to the patient experiencing a stroke last month. EMS arrived a few minutes after the second EPI-PEN dose and patient was transported to the hospital for evaluation. Facility reported that patient went home that afternoon but did not provide details. Based on my assessment of patient's symptoms and behavior, I feel it is likely that she experienced either an acute panic attack or anaphylaxis due to vaccine administration. I called the patient today (the day after the incident) and she confirms that she received treatment for an anaphylactic reaction to the Moderna COVID shot and is doing well without any lasting adverse effects.
LAB_DATA: Patient was transported by EMS to nearby  Hospital emergency room. Patient reported receiving steroids, Benadryl, and epinephrine but I was not able to speak to anyone at the hospital for information regarding any medical tests or laboratory results.
OTHER_MEDS: PATIENT REPORTS TAKING MEDICATION FOR DEPRESSION, ANXIETY, AND GERD BUT DOES NOT REMEMBER THE NAMES OF THE MEDICATION
CUR_ILL: DEPRESSION, ANXIETY, GERD, STROKE 2 MONTHS AGO

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient became lightheaded at approximately 11:10 a.m. which was 9 minutes after administration of the vaccine.  The patient had expressed some anxiety about receiving the vaccine but wanted to receive it. The patient complained of lightheadedness and we lowered her to the floor with feet elevated. Her blood pressure had lowered significantly (60/40 approximately). Patient began to feel better and sat back in her chair. She again began to complain of lightheadedness and was lowered to the floor with feet elevated once more. Patients stayed in this position for several minutes. When her blood pressure was rechecked, it had risen back to 118/78. Patient felt much better and also ate some crackers and drank some water. Patient's blood pressure was checked a final time in a seated position after approximately 20 minutes and her blood pressure was 118/82. Patient reported having an event like this 36 years ago after her first visit to an OB/GYN and was similarly nervous that day. Patient was counseled extensively on preventing future lightheadedness and signs of any vaccine related adverse event. After approximately 45 minutes of observation from the event, patient was driven home by her husband.

The patient received the vaccine at approximately 1:30. They were observed for the standard 15 minute wait time at which time they complained of some mild numbness to their arm. The patient felt well enough to return to work after the 15 minute observation time. They returned approximately 20 to 30 minutes later complaining of more numbness and some dizziness. She (the patient) was told to continue to monitor symptoms and alert anyone of worsening side effects or symptoms. The patient returned to the room again and was now complaining of nausea. She was offered Benadryl but patient refused stating " I cant have Benadryl" after multiple times of the pharmacist(s)  offering Benadryl. Patient stated they sometimes take Claritin so they were instructed to take it and lie down in an area where staff could monitor her. At about 3:30 another staff member came into the vaccination room and alerted the pharmacist they were having a hard time keeping to patient awake.  Upon arrival at the patient's side they were coughing and seemed to be in a state of drowsiness. They were linked to a vitals monitor by the staff. BP: 170/110 O2: 96-100% HR between 80 and 90.  Approximately 2 minutes after arrival at patient's side 911 was called. Pharmacist retrieved the Epi-Pen and was on standby if administration was needed.  The patient was moved to a chair and vomited multiple times over the course of a few minutes. The Patient was able to vocalize and stated they felt "aweful" and has some difficulty swallowing, and when asked if they were short of breath they stated "a little." Over the next 5 minutes (approx.) the patient's BP went down to 152/90'S and O2 saturation was holding at 97-100%. Epinephrine was not administered during this time as patient was breathing and did not appear to have hives. Emergency medical services arrived about 5 minutes but within 10 minutes after the call was placed. EMS then took over care  for the patient. EMS was told of condition and that epinephrine was not administered at this time. After patient assessment by EMS they also declined to use epinephrine. At around 3:40 the patient was transferred to a transport bed and was taken away by ambulance.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Received first in a series of 2 injections for the Moderna COVID-19 vaccine on 12/30/2020. Headache, fatigue, joint pain  were noted for approximately after 24-72 hours and again on days 6 and 7 after injection, along with red circular rash at injection site that was about size of a quarter on right upper arm that became  apparent 24 hours after injection. Rash was also hot to the touch, and itchy.  Approximately on day 6 after injection, rash became raised, felt firm and spread in diameter to  approximately 3-3.5 inches, rash was raised and firm off and on for several days.  By day 12 after injection, rash was starting to lighten in color but was continuing to grow in size to approximately 5 inches in diameter, it was no longer raised or firm, but continued to be hot to the touch and itchy, even with daily use of oral Benadryl and Loratadine . Out of concern that it was not going away on its own contacted PCP on day 14 post vaccine and notified of  situation and office visit made on day 15 post vaccine on 1/14/21 for further assessment. PCP prescribed course of antibiotics (Bactrim x 10 days) as could not  determine if it was  truly infection or localized immune response, or combination of both. Was also prescribed  5 day course of steroids (prednisone) to take prior to and after next COVID vaccine injection.

At 6 days after my second COVID-19 Pfizer vaccine (first dose given 12/17/20), I had acute onset of chest pain and shortness of breath prompting a trip to the Emergency Department.  A chest CT Angio to rule out pulmonary embolus was done and negative for pulmonary embolus. My EKG showed some mild ST changes and a troponin I level was elevated at 0.08 (normal 0.04). Subsequent troponin levels 90 minutes apart showed a rising troponin at 0.18 and 0.38. An echocardiogram was performed which showed regional wall motion abnormalities consistent with Takotsubo cardiomyopathy and an ejection fraction of 45%. I was then taken to cardiac catheterization lab for coronary angiograms which were normal. My LV angiogram was consistent with Takotsubo cardiomyopathy and my LVEDP was elevated. I was started on a beta blocker and sent home the following day.
LAB_DATA: See above Troponin elevated 1/14/21 Abnormal EKG 1/14/21 Abnormal ECHOcardiogram 1/14/21 Takotsubo Cardiomyopathy (also known as stress induced cardiomyopathy)  Normal coronary angiogram  1/14/21

I had no pain or discomfort immediately after the shot, during the 15 minute observation period, or an hour after. About 2 hours later (at 2:00 pm), I developed some hives around my neck, and the part of my arm near the injection site started to become more and more sore. I applied Benadryl to the hives and they went away. However, my left arm hurt to touch or move, much worse than any vaccine I've had before (flu, HPV). That night, I had trouble sleeping because the discomfort because of the sore left arm. I also could not sleep because of chest tightness and pressure, which worsened when lying down, but that pressure did not progress to the point of wheezing (I have asthma).  Sleeping on my back was the only option because sleeping on either side was painful, which worsened the chest pressure. When I woke up, my fingers felt stiff and I had joint pain in both hands, more so in my left hand. Throughout this, I did not see any redness on my arm. This day it was agonizing to move my left arm. I could pick things up, but raising it above my the height of my waist or twisting it behind my back to get on my backpack was near impossible and was avoided. The chest pressure went away. The second night, I still had trouble sleeping, but the pain was much better, although I still could not sleep on my side. When I woke up, I had no more joint pain. That day, although the left arm was still sore, I could move it pretty well. If I made too strong of a movement, it felt like the injection site would tense up, the pain would slowly ramp up, and then diminish. That afternoon, at 4:30, I was able to play tennis with minimal soreness, and that night, I was able to sleep on my side. The following day, I had a cough, but that might have been because I didn't dress for the weather, and experiences close to zero soreness.

1/12 0715: Received Pfizer covid-19 vaccine dose 2 at end of shift. Went home to sleep after waiting 15 min.  1630: Woke up. Felt more tired than usual.  1900: Arrived at work. Felt fatigue and sore arm.  2000: Felt sore arm, fatigue, and mild HA. Drank coffee and this helped with fatigue and HA. 2100: Mild nausea starts. Still have sore arm. Less fatigue, no HA. Still able to eat with the nausea. 2200: Developed chills. I was putting up curtains in an isolation room and had to pause halfway through due to being short of breath as if I'd done something strenuous. I then was short of breath again walking specimens to lab, which is unusual for me. Walking samples to lab involves walking 400 ft and going up and down 1 flight of stairs.  2300: Coworkers keep asking me why I'm always out of breath. They are concerned. Chills are worse now and I go from feeling normal to feeling cold. My hands are like ice and I am gripping my arms to keep warm. I walk 2 samples to lab and each time I am dizzy on the way back. By the 2nd time I have to hold the wall to keep balance. I can no longer hide the side effects and a coworker offers me 650mg Tylenol. I gladly accept. I measure my spO2 and it is 97%.  1/13 0530: I am almost back to normal other than feeling fatigued.  0815: I get home and go to bed. My feet are ice cold so I have to wear socks, but my hands feel normal temperature. I feel like my blanket isn't warm enough.  1330: I wake up and feel absolutely miserable. I am going between having chills to having a hot flash. I can't seem to will myself to leave bed. I'm pretty sure I have a fever, which I haven't had in over 10 years. My mouth is completely dry.  1400: I manage to roll out of bed and take my temperature, which is 101.3F. I feel an overall malaise and keep getting periodic hot flashes, but manage to make it downstairs and I mix 1 liquid IV electrolyte packet w/ 24fl oz. water. I drank the whole thing. I also cooked myself some dumplings and 1 waffle w/ maple syrup due to feeling much hungrier than usual.  1430: I take 1000mg Extra Strength Tylenol after eating.  1830: I feel almost normal except for significant fatigue and go to bed.  1/14 0430: I wake up and feel completely normal. No fatigue. Go about my day as normal. 1545: Suddenly I feel lightheadedness and mild HA. Have trouble with inattention (ex. not following w/ conversation or forgetting what people just said, or listening but not registering, or can't find the words to respond or answers to a question.). I take my Vitals: 117/95, spO2 85%, HR 63. I then try taking a couple deep breaths and spO2 increases to 98% and lightheadedness and HA go away. Then a few minutes later lightheadedness and HA begin again and spO2 is 80-90%. Then I take 2 deep breaths and spO2 is 98% and HA and dizziness improves. This repeats several times and I grow concerned. My hands are cold and the pulse oximeter is $30 from Amazon. However, I used the pulse ox on my mother and she was 97% consistently every time without fail. I also used pulse ox on myself when perfectly healthy and same thing it was 98%+ every time. This is why I was now worried. 1630: I take Tylenol since this seems to have helped with any and every symptom I've had so far and book an Urgent Care appointment.  1700: I get up to take a shower and feel extremely dizzy to the point where I'm worried I might fall. I stumble into the bathroom holding the wall. I take spO2 and it is 87%.  1800: I show up to Urgent Care and after the shower I feel my hands are warm now. At Urgent Care they are using  pulse oximeters and I am spO2 99% and HR 64. So they chalk it up to my crappy Amazon pulse ox and they tell me to hang in there. Perhaps if I had not taken a shower before going there it may have been a different story? Hard to say now. Also the Tylenol may have started to work by then.  2200: I am still inattentive, spacey, lightheaded, and fatigued. I then fell asleep on the couch without realizing.  1/15 0230: I wake up and feel fatigued with brain fog, but no more lightheadedness.  0630: I go back to bed because I'm too sleepy.

Headache, Myalgia, Arthralgia, Fever & Tachycardia Narrative:  She reported having a temp of 104. She is RN house supervisor, she was able to reduce her temperature to 103.8 after tylenol. She as asked to call her PCP for recommendations. She was asked to go to E.D. She went to the E.D. on 1/7/21 had high fever of 104.3, dehydrated and tachycardic with pulse of 130. She was treated with I.V. tylenol, and given two liters of Fluids. She was sent home with normal pulse of 78, and temp down to 100.9. Today 1/8/21 she continues to run a fever, high of 101. She is to return to the E.D. if temp continues. She apparently had edema and rash on palms after first dose of COVID 19, so staff in COVID 19 vaccination clinic pre medicated her with benadryl 25mg. po.
PRIOR_VAX: yes she had reaction to first shot, with edema and rash on palms.

face swelling, swelling around belly button Narrative:  Has contacted her PCP, states she has had reactions to vaccines in the past. Bursitis in shoulder and swelling in leg after Influenza vaccines in the past, bursitis caused her rotator cuff to rupture. Both times her swelling lasted for weeks. States she fell asleep this morning, when she awoke, her face around her eyes, cheeks and lips were swollen. She is not having any difficulty breathing, and states her throat is not swelling. She has been in touch with her colleagues who are all providers who have informed her that this reaction is due to her face fillers. She also mentions some swelling around her belly button where she had threading about a year ago. Her PCP is prescribing her Prednisone and an antihistamine, she has been taking Zyrtec which she believes has helped prevent her from swelling more than she already has. She is being monitored at home by her daughter and knows to call 9-1-1 or to to the nearest hospital if her reaction worsens.
PRIOR_VAX: yes- Flu vaccine-bursitis caused rotator cuff to rupture; also had Flu vaccine in left thigh and it welted x2 weeks; Flublock- s

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient had her first Moderna COVID vaccination at 4:00 PM today and 5 min later felt dizziness, worsening, associated with headache, nausea, sore throat, hot flashes, and dizziness is from side to side when she looks at her phone, no dizziness when she does not look at it. Patient primary complaint is headache on bilateral temples. All other symptoms resolved, and no dizziness if not looking at phone.  Patient has history of headaches, similar in quality, but this is more intense (6/10 intensity, less than her scoliosis pains, but more than usual headache pain), but otherwise the same, pounding sensation, and she can feel throbbing. Headache is about the same currently. Started simultaneously as dizziness, immediately, unchanged. No changes in vision. Peak intensity of headache around 30 min after onset, peak at 4:30 or so.  Patient notified the vaccine clinic staff and was instructed to be observed in another area, and did not improve. Patient remembered that her initial blood pressure was low and it fluctuated. Patient was then sent to the ED.  Upon initial assessment in the Emergency Department 2 hours after her initial injection, the assessment is likely vasovagal near syncope with tension headache, rather than true allergic reaction. Given metoclopramide, diphenhydramine, normal saline, and obtained labs.
LAB_DATA: Unremarkable labs, CT head scan negative for acute pathology (patient under 6 hours presentation, and effectively ruled out intracranial bleeding, which was less likely), and patient improved, tolerating oral diet, ambulatory.
ALLERGIES: Acetic acid otic drops causes stinging sensation in ear with redness Mupirocin causes rash

I received the above Pfizer COVID-19 vaccine around 12:45 PM, within about 3-5 minutes of receiving the vaccine and standing in line to check out I suddenly felt I was going to loss consciousness/collapse so started lowering myself to the ground and then became unconscious and fell.  Healthcare staff informed me I was unconscious for about 20-30 seconds. I woke up and initially felt confused, but quickly realized what had happened.  Then I felt nauseated, had some stomach cramps and thought I was going to have diarrhea.  They considered giving me Epi for possible anaphylaxis, but I requested they observe further for any skin reaction/hives, airway symptoms, etc given I was skeptical the syncope may have been fully or partially related to the amlodipine I took that morning.  Symptoms slowly improved over 20-30 minutes, but the lightheaded feeling and nauseated lasted hours.  No Epipen, medications, or interventions were needed.
OTHER_MEDS: amlodipine 2.5 mg, Vitamin D3 1,000 IU PO, aspirin 81 mg - that morning
HISTORY: asthma, Raynaud's, possible inflammatory arthritis/possible mild rheumatoid arthritis, migraine headaches

Within 2 minutes post vaccination i started feeling loss of sense of myself. I could not pinpoint if i felt dizzy or vertiginous. Felt like i was off balance and i was super vernous to walk. Vertiginous episodes come and go with peaks for at least 10 times. The whole episode lasted 4 hours until i felt going back to myself.   I was provided water, 1 L and orange juice, there was epi available. No anaphylactic symptoms, no shortness of breath.   I drank 1,5 L of fluids and then my BP was checked 120/80, HR 80s.  I note that i never felt syncopal,  no diaphoresis, nausea, nor darkened vision and i was fully interactive with the bystanders.  Note, i am a critical care intensivist so i had full grasp of the issue but i could now quite describe the sensation of this acute loss of instability. The best way to describe this was vertigo. Similar episode occured at the first vaccine with COVID, occured after 10 minutes and lasted no more than 30 seconds. I didnt report that then because i thought it was just dehydration.
LAB_DATA: Remained for observation approximately 50 minutes, blood pressure was checked Then i decided to walk to my office. I had sense of instability. The room was not spinning itself, but myself i felt like i was easy to go off balance if i would look right or left or down to my phone. I was focusing my eyes to a target distance to concentrate

Patient complained of feeling light-headed and a little dizzy at 10 minutes post-administration.  Pulse-oximetry applied revealed normal spO2, but tachycardia to 140bpm (this patient's resting HR is approximately 55-65).  Apple Watch data confirmed rapid increase in HR at that moment.  BP increased from normal baseline to about 150-160 SBP.  No chest pain reported.  No signs/symptoms of anaphylaxis (rash, wheezing, etc.).  HR gradually recovered to normal levels within 30 minutes and patient was released after 60 min observation.  Patient reported generalized fatigue in weeks following injection.   Nineteen (19) days after injection, patient developed unprovoked resting tachycardia to approximately 180bpm (following some moderate weigh-lifting exercise).  Symptoms did no resolve sufficiently and patient was transported by EMS to ER for evaluation
LAB_DATA: On second event (day 19) patient underwent 12 lead ECG (sinus tachycardia with incomplete RBBB).  CT Chest with IVC showed no abnormal findings.  Labs including CBC, BMP, CRP, cardiac troponins were all WNL.  Patient also had normal thyroid function studies (TSH, FT4, T3) about 2 weeks prior. 2-dimentional echocardiogram was normal.  Patient underwent treadmill stress test with nuclear imaging one week following ED visit which was also normal (no findings of ischemia).  Patient is currently wearing a 30-day cardiac event monitor.  He is still experiencing fatigue and decreased exercise capacity (but no limitations in activity otherwise)

SYMPTOM_TEXT: She did not have any problems immediately after the shot or waiting period.  She went back to work and all was normal until she went to meeting.  It was a little less than 4 hours after the shot.  She asked to have her temperature checked, then fell on the floor and collapsed. Her BP was 190/110, and her HR was very high, beating out of her throat and throat swelled up � she could barely breathe.  Normally, her BP is 120/80 and HR is usually around 68 BPM. She could not move her legs or arms, but she could move fingers.  This is an anaphylactic seizure that acts like a stroke � severe slurring of speech, cannot close eyes (but vision blurred), throat swells up and constricts airway, and she yells out uncontrollably.  She shivered like she was very cold, but she did not have any convulsions.  It lasted around 20 minutes. EMT who took care of her.  She could hear everything going on, but her vision was very blurry (could not see).  She was taken to Hospital. They checked her for stroke, did a CAT scan, and took her blood.  Everything came out normal.  She felt fine after it was over.  She was released at 8 pm to go home, and she walked out on her own. She feels that the 1,2-distearoyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine [DSPC] in the vaccine may be what triggered her reaction as she thinks it may be closely related to steroids. She will NOT take the 2nd shot on advice of doctor.  Dr. has been her physician for 10 years.  Previous History:  Seizure reaction to steroids � happened 4 hours after took the steroid � this same anaphylactic like seizure happened with the steroid, exactly.  Present at that event were several people.   Patient says that this is the exact same reaction she had both when she took the steroid and following the COVID vaccine.
LAB_DATA: BP - 190/110 (normal 120/80)/CAT scan = normal/Took blood work - no bad results
ALLERGIES: Seizure reaction to steroids in the past/Penicillin & Sulfa are anaphylaxis/Codeine makes her have vertigo and disrupts her breathing

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Nurse administrating vaccine used the syringe  system provided with the vaccine. Upon removal of the needle, the nurse laid the syringe on the table and simultaneously the patient felt a wet spray on her arm. The patient (an infectious diseases specialist very familiar with vaccine administration) observed that the needle was aimed at her and not retracted at all. The proper use of the brand of safety syringe would result in the needle retracting into the syringe before  the administrator moves the syringe hub off the injection site of the arm. Given the needle was not retracted and the patient was sprayed with fluid, I conclude the patient received at best a partial dose.  I will invalidate this dose in Epic (deleting it with the reasons quantity not sufficient) and order a follow-up visit where the patient can receive a valid second dose. We will not wait any minimum interval between this invalid dose and the valid dose.

12/29/2020- Received the Moderna Vaccine - no pain or problems until 01/04/2021 01/04/2021- Before bedtime my injection site from the Moderna Vaccine became itchy.  01/05/2020- Woke up to a swollen arm (about 3 times the size of my right arm) and the start of a rash (the size of a softball) Was in significant pain and unable to lift my arm. I called the nurse hotline where I received the vaccine. I was told to go to the ER immediately. The ER doctor informed me that they had been seeing this and that their personal vaccine location swelled up as well but went away a few days later. ER doctor gave me Benadryl cream (I can not ingest Benadryl due to an opposite reaction, I become extremely anxious.) The ER doctor informed me that the Benadryl cream wouldn't cause the same reaction. I was sent home with the cream and a wrap. Upon arriving home my rash grew exponentially over the following days. The site became hot (even after icing it) It remained itchy and painful.  01/11/2021- Went to primary care doctor. The rash and swelling had decreased although you could still see the ring of the rash. At this point, my hand was becoming numb after doing daily activities including typing. My palm and thumb area started to turn purplish/blueish when I would type for less than 20 seconds. The doctor told me they would start to reach out to other providers and figure out how to best move forward. In the meantime, there wasn't much to do besides wait and see what happens.  01/13/2021- Woke up throughout the night due to continued pain at the injection site. Called the primary care doctor who wasn't in the office, waited for a call back from their nurse but due delayed call back and  increased pain and numbness went to urgent care (which is under the same practice as primary care). The urgent care doctor performed tests regarding pinched nerve shoulder (as they believed I had a pinched nerve in my shoulder) and ordered an x-ray. The x-ray showed tissue damage but nothing else. I was not experiencing shoulder pain, although during one of the shoulder tests I found more discomfort in my left should (injection arm) than my right arm. Therefore, the primary care doctor thought I was experiencing a pinched nerve in my shoulder.  01/14/2021 - Primary care doctor called and informed me they had spoken with the infectious disease doctor in the area who informed them that they have been seeing a similar reaction amongst other people. (7 days after inject, swelling and rash) The infectious disease doctor reported they hadn't seen numbness. The primary care doctor advised me to wait 2 weeks to see how symptoms change before performing additional tests. The primary care doctor also advised me after speaking with the infectious disease doctor to not take the second shot.  01/16/2021- still experiencing issues with daily functioning. Still experiencing numbness in hand and arm. Still experiencing redness around the injection site (although much better still flairs up at moments)   Side note: 01/03/2021 - Went cross country skiing, did fall backwards but did NOT fall on arm.  Also confusion remains if  I was supposed to report this or if the primary care doctor/ER doctor reported this, therefore, urgent care doctor told me to report this reaction.
LAB_DATA: 01/13/2021 - Xray and pinched nerve shoulder tests
