SYMPTOM_TEXT: On Friday, January 15 at approximately 6 PM while seated in a reclining chair watching television I started to develop hives below my right gluteal fold. Over the next six hours  approximately 300 hives appeared on my skin. They were very itchy. At approximately midnight my lip began to swell and being a certified registered nurse anesthetist,  who lives alone, I knew it was time to head to the ER. Prior to going to the ER  I  cleaned the lesions With alcohol, took prednisone 10 mg PO,  and applied hydrocortisone cream.    In the ER, I was given Benadryl 50 mg PO and Pepcid 20 mg and observed for one hour. The hives remained but there was no respiratory compromise. Approximately six hours later the hives were still increasing in size and number, were unbearably itchy and my swollen lips had not subsided.  I took Claritin 10 mg PO and returned to the same ER and was given Epinephrine 0.3 mg IM, prednisone 20 mg po and observed for three hours. The hives did not decrease and again there was no respiratory compromise so I was sent home on prednisone And a H-1 blocker.  Of note, both my palms and lips have been bright cherry red.     I finished a five day course of Macrobid on January 13 at 10 AM.    Final diagnosis:  Alergic  reaction
OTHER_MEDS: Losartan, metoprolol, simvastatin, Zoloft, calcium, vitamin D, vitamin B 12, Macrobid,   Multivitamin with iron.
HISTORY: HTN,   HIGH CHOLESTEROL,   S/P. ROUX-N-Y,  depression.

I received my first dose of the Pfizer COVID vaccine at approximately 9:15am on Thursday, January 14, 2021 in my right arm.  Almost immediately, I felt a pain go down to my wrist and across my chest. We pulled into the waiting area and around five minutes after the injection the right side of my face went numb., the pain had left my arm and chest by the time.  The nurse reacted by calling the emergency room and sending me there.
LAB_DATA: I arrived at the emergency room at approximately 9:30 am on Thursday, January 14, 2021.  They immediately ran an EKG, and did observations on me for about an hour and a half.  They made me smile, raise my eyebrows up and down, stick my tongue out, and puff my cheeks out.  I could do all of those things.  They then gave me a Benadryl and two prednisone pills and then discharged me, and told me to follow up with my primary care physician.  After leaving the hospital I experienced pain in my jaw and teeth on the right side , a migraine headache, and neck pain.  Th next  day I still had the jaw and teeth pain And slight swelling in the right side of my face, and some drooling when talking or eating,  and called my primary care physician, he is out of the office until Tuesday, January 19th, but I spoke with the nurse practioner who gave me a 12 day prescription for Prednisone and said she would communicate with the doctor when he returned to the office.  I began the prednisone treatment on Friday, January 15, 2021.  As of today, Saturday, January 16, 2021, I still have facial numbness on the right side of my face (unchanged since Thursday), slight swelling of the right side of my face, jaw and teeth pain in the right side, And sleepiness in my right eye and nose area.
OTHER_MEDS: Depakote for migraines, Enskyce birth control pills

After my first vaccine (EK5730--on 12/26/20), I had absolutely NO reactions. The second one was quite a different matter.   14 hours after the shot, I developed shaking chills. The next day I had myalgias and arthralgias pretty much all over. It was that "run over by a truck" feeling of the flu. Headache, fatigue followed. Appetite was down. No fever.   Slept for many hours.   Now in my third day after the vaccine and not feeling better.   Still, I remain grateful that I was immunized and am taking the optimistic spin that this kind of intense reaction shows my immune system is responding strongly and nicely to the vaccine.  It is miserable though, particularly since the first one was so benign.   I am a family doctor (MD) and am torn between discussing this in my weekly health column which may dissuade patients, some already on the fence, from getting vaccinated. I saw the FDA info confirming higher incidence of side effects with second shot, which was definitely the case with me.

Eight days after receiving the vaccine (1/7/2021) I noticed my upper left arm felt hard when I touched it; no discomfort.  Later the same day after returning home from work I changed my clothing and noted my upper left arm was swollen, very red and felt hot when I touched it.  The red/swollen area extended from just below where I received the vaccine to just above the elbow.  I thought maybe I had a spider bite, but couldn't find anything that looked like the site of a bite.  The following day I coincidentally had an appointment for my annual physical, so I mentioned it to my physician.  He didn't see anything that looked like a bite, but did see the redness and swelling.  The swelling subsided after a couple days.  The red color on my skin faded and was totally gone on 1/14/2021.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: ?Within the first 15 minutes - injection site felt hot (right arm).   ?Within the first hour - right arm felt heavy with some numbness/tingling that lasted less than 10 minutes.   ?3 hours post vaccine - mild arm soreness with ROM, but not to the touch.   ?7 hours post vaccine - I felt very fatigued. I could have gone to bed at 1600. I could barely keep my eyes open.   ?8 hours post vaccine - fatigue was still very much present, moderate arm soreness with ROM and now to the touch. I felt very feverish, but was afebrile.   ?10 hours post vaccine - fatigue was a little better because I had taken an hour nap. Body aches and headache had set in, and I still felt feverish without a fever. I couldn?t stop shivering. I needed to be under multiple blankets with long sleeves, pants and thick socks on to feel even a little bit warm.   ?13.5 hours post vaccine - fatigue and body aches had worsened. It?s a struggle to go from laying to sitting and sitting to standing. I even fell back down to the couch a few times because I didn?t have the strength to stand up all the way. Right arm soreness has progressed enough that lifting up a water bottle was a struggle, and I could not lay on my right side. My temp is now 101.4�.   ?I tossed and turned between 0200-0630 shivering and aching all over. I slept with my entire body (even my head) under the blankets to try to stay warm. My head was throbbing. I got up at 0630 to take some Tylenol and woke up sometime between 0630 and 1030 drenched in sweat, so I?m assuming I had another fever.   ?30.5 hours post vaccine - it?s now January 1st. Body aches/stiffness, headache, fatigue, right arm soreness still very present. Switching any type of body position was a struggle. Temp is 101.2� now. I got out of bed at 1045 and got back in bed at 1200. I stayed in bed until 1845.   ?48 hours post vaccine - slight headache and right arm soreness. Right arm ROM is very doable again. My neck, shoulders and hips are sore, but much better. Fatigue is gone. I?m able to move around fine without any struggle. I still have SOB from March, but I feel like over the last 24 hours it?s worsened a bit.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Sore arm, mild cold symptoms on Day 1 & 2, was expected, didn't worry. Then all was normal again until Day 9, which was 1/11/21 appx 2:00 am. Sore arm awakened me. Area at and below injection site red, swollen, about 2" x 2" diameter. By 2:00PM, area had grown to 7" x 4", very swollen, very warm to touch, burning sensation. Got home from work about 7:00pm, took benadryl, applied cool compress and massage, went to sleep. (Had called my doctors office, was waiting for call back.) Next morning about 4:00am, arm didn't hurt as much, was less red and swollen, but now itched very much. Whole body felt itchy, including inside my ears. I called out sick to work, took more benadryl, and planned to go to urgent care if needed. Doctor called me about 10:00am, waking me from benadryl sleep. They advised observation if no worsening, urgent care if it did. Since then, flat red patch on injection area, mild itch, mild swelling. Co worker just informed us she had same symptoms today (got her vaccine on 1/5/21) & is diagnosed cellulitis & prescribed antibiotics, so now I'm worried about my arm again, and worried about the lot number and reporting this reaction.

intermittent bilateral peripheralal neuropathy in hands and feet Narrative:  Per his PCP "He described intermittent numbness, tingling, which is sometimes painful, involving fingertips and toes. Sx are most prominent when driving or in bed preparing to sleep. He consulted his PCP, who is an NP. She checked HbA1c and found it normal. She prescribed gabapentin 100mg daily prn, which patient has not used. There were no reports of peripheral neuropathy in the FDA documents for the Pfizer vaccine. Intermittent symptoms are unusual for peripheral neuropathy. Hyperventilation can cause intermittent numbness and tingling of fingers and toes.At this time I would characterize his symptoms as unexplained. Although it is unlikely, I cannot rule out a relationship to the vaccine. Due to concern that the symptoms could be an early symptom of a neurologic condition that has not yet fully manifested, I advised him to cancel his appt for the second dose, and wait to see how if his symptoms progress. If his symptoms resolve, he could schedule the second dose of vaccine at a later date. While the 21 day interval is ideal, CDC has advised that there is no outer limit to when the second dose may be administered."

vasovagal response Narrative:  Initial Vital Signs: Temp: BP: 83/38 HR: 44 RR: O2 Sat: Primary Reason for Call: CODE WHITE in vaccination observation area Staff concern, worried Explain: pale, diaphoretic Situation: Pt received covid vaccine at 0802-0805 staff noticed that pt was pale and diaphoretic, laid pt on the floor, BP in the 60's, On arrival pt resting on floor a/o x3. States that this happens with injections. Report BP 83/38, 44. After a period of time BP increased to 116/72, 64. Pt assisted to wc with BP sitting 125/81, 70, taken to the ED for evaluation and observation. Nurse who administered the vaccine stated the patient said she was afraid of needles and was very nervous prior to the injection. ED provider: FEMALE who presents to the Emergency Dept. "passed out after getting the Covid shot". Triage note as above, patient went for covid vaccine this morning and afterwards and she felt dizzy and passed out. She is known for having passing out with previous vaccination as well. No preceding chest discomfort, feeling fine now no nausea vomiting or other focal complaints. She regained consciousness soon after that.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Sore arm at the injection site 24 hours post vaccine then symptoms  of nausea, weakness, tired, headache started 12/20/2020, 4 days post the vaccine. Went to the ER on the 12/21/20-12/22/20 due to increase headache, vomiting, diarrhea, dizzy, dry cough, weak/extremely fatigue. At the ER was given IV fluid, Zofran, Phenergan, tested for the Flu and Covid, also had blood work. All my blood work came back in normal ranges, FLU and Covid test were negative as well. Discharged from the ER with Phenergan, the next 3 days I had a migraine and had to be in a dark room with lights off, still very dizzy, tired, shortness of breath with movement, could not eat it made me nauseas. Called for follow up with PCP he then put me on steroids, for 7 days. 12/28 called PCP office again, was put on another round of steroid treatment with antibiotic. Was off work from 12/21/2020-01/02/21 due to the sickness post the vaccine

On the first day after the injection (1/15/201) the arm was still sore and I still felt tired - burning/freezing sensation had ceased. On the second day after the injection (1/16/2021) the left arm was not sore and I felt better, but at 11:00 a.m. the vein in the left temple burst and bled until about 6:00 p.m. Continuous throbbing pain across the forehead the entire day. The  middle of the forehead is covered with red dots; the area near the left eye has a number of open, bloody lesions; the area below the temple (left cheek) is black and blue. There are also two bright red spots on my left knee - but no bleeding. Nausea was slight, but present during the entire day on Saturday and Sunday. Since the hospitals have Covid 19 patients and I do not have a car, I stayed home and rested in bed.  Today on Sunday (1/17/2021) I can sit up and walk around somewhat; the throbbing pain in the head has ceased. The lesions are still vivid red , but slowly forming a crust.  Will make contact with my doctor  on Monday, when the office is open.

Day 1 to 2---Left arm tenderness at the site for 2 days, no redness/rash/lump. Day 3---no side effects Day 4 to Day 5---At about 8 pm, I noticed slight swelling underneath my left eye, that looked like a bag.  My face was also red.  The sides of my face, jaw line,  & both sides of my neck were itchy.  I went to bed since I was supposed to work the next morning at 6 AM (OB Nurse).  I work up at 4:15 AM & my face was quite swollen, specifically my left side, my face & neck was warm to the touch &  itchy.  I immediately took 50mg of Benadryl & called my internal medicine doctor. Day 5---I was to be seen in the clinic at 7:00 AM.  The Benadryl helped some.  I was not having any breathing difficulty.  I was prescribed 5 days of Prednisone.  By about 1:00 PM,  the swelling was worsening & my lips were tingling.  I called the doctor again & they told me to go to the ER.  I never had issues with my airway.   The swelling was always worse on my left side of my face.  I received IV fluids & Solumedrol & was discharged with an epi pen, & told to continue the Benadryl, Prednisone, & Pepcid bid.  CoVid test done in ER was negative. Day 6---The facial swelling/redness/itching remained but was improved.  I was very tired. Day 7---Same as Day 6, but less swelling. Day 8---Facial swelling/redness/itching gone, but tiredness remained.  Started to notice a chest heaviness/feeling of constant excitement in the center of my chest, even when at rest. Day 9-10---Tiredness remained.  Intermittent Chest heaviness/feeling of excitement in the center of my chest remained. Day 11---Feeling more normal.
HISTORY: None (hx of childhood exercise-induced asthma, 4 total pregnancies & thyroiditis only after pregnancy #3)

I was nauseous. I believed I was going to faint. My blood pressure spiked.   I noticed getting hotter and hotter  within 5 or 10 minutes of the shot. I removed some outer clothing, but I still kept getting hotter.  Then I noticed I was very light headed. Then I noticed I was sweating. I was very clammy and later on, a woman attendant said she could see the sweat on my. The headache began in the back of my neck. I thought I was going to faint. I because nauseous. My thinking became unclear.  After about 15 minutes of this continuing to get worse, I called over the paramedics. They took my blood pressure and said it was very high. They checked my heart beat, oxygen level, lungs, and blood pressure. They checked my blood pressure again, and then again maybe 15 or so minutes after the second time and they reported to me that it was going down. I continued to not feel well and the worst of it lasted for about an hour and now, 2 full days later I still do not feel well.   Yesterday, 1 day after the shot, I barely got off the couch.   Today, my vision is blurry, I am still light headed, and still feel dizzy. My headache has diminished. My thinking is still foggy.  I do not feel safe to drive.  As far as treatment, I just sat still. I had eaten breakfast and lunch (ate lunch within an hour of the shot, but was given a ginger all and 2 cookies, which I ate. After I felt well enough to get up, I walked around the facility for a few minutes, then I went outside in the cold fresh air and continued to walk for a bit. I then drove home and stayed on the couch.   I do want to state (and no where on here does it ask about this) so I am putting it here: I have only ever gotten a small pox and polio vaccination as a child, a Hep B shot four decades ago, and tetanus/whooping cough shots. I also take no medications and throughout my lifetime I have only taken a few.  So, when the early pre-vaccine assessments ask about allergic reactions to injections of vaccines, I answered no because I barely ever had any. No pre-vaccination assessments also said that no adverse reactions to oral medications were a problem. And there was no where in the early assessments to give u that info. I did say, yes, about having immune system issues on the online assessment, and I told the attendant at the time of check in. It is unidentified as far as it having a name, but I have seen a Rheumatologist last spring and she ruled out Lupis. I get sick easily with colds, so I believe I have a weak immune system.
LAB_DATA: none I will be calling my doctor tomorrow if they are open on the holiday to see what they think I need to do.
CUR_ILL: I have/had no known illnesses at the time of the vaccination.
HISTORY: I am seeing various specialist to uncover something that is not identified. I had Lyme disease several times and have had issues ever since the first infection. Those issues have continued through the years and some of them are being addressed by the specialists, but nothing has been identified at this time.  I do get sick with colds very easily and often.
ALLERGIES: Yes. I am allergic to Tobramycin and Dexamethasone ophthalmic Suspension: my Ophthalmologist suggested the allergic reaction was from the preservative in this medicine.  I am allergic to Keflex. I am allergic to mold. I can not use anychemical cleaners such as Windex, nor any scented products such as laundry detergent/dish liquid/perfume/candles/cleaners/etc. I saw an allergist, but they do not test for chemicals only natural substances, thusly, I came out of there knowing I had a mold allergy, but no test for the preservatives/chemicals/scented perfumes/etc.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: One week post-vaccine injection, sharp pains began on and off on the left side of my face. These moved from cheek to jaw to lip to left eye and at the nasal base. There was also stabbing pain in the left eye.  I thought this was due to just being tired from long days at work, but I was also aware it might have been related to the vaccine. Therefore, I took 1600 mg of acyclovir I had on hand to prevent occasional cold sores and went to sleep. The following day, unfortunately, these sharp pains persisted on and off throughout the day. I retook acyclovir and went to work. I reported this to my PCP, and she thought it was unrelated to the vaccine. I spoke with surgeons in my office, and after examination, they both clearly said it was a reaction in my 5th cranial nerve. They both recommended prednisone or methylprednisolone, but my PCP didn't agree, and therefore, I did not receive a prescription for prednisone. I retook acyclovir, and by the following afternoon of  Friday, January 15, I was no longer experiencing sharp pains on the left side of my face.
LAB_DATA: N/A  No tests were ordered related to this event.

Upon awakening the morning after the vaccination, I experienced swelling in my ankles, feet and fingers I also experienced swelling in my face where I had received filler injections six months ago. I also experienced feeling very spacey and foggy in addition to ringing in my ears, pins and needles all over my skin as well as a burning sensation on my upper back, buttocks and thighs.  Finally,  I felt extremely fatigued and lethargic.  I had no fever or headache but had soreness at the injection site.  I dosed with  600 mg of ibuprofen b.i.d. the first day as well as 50 mg of Benadryl at bedtime.  While I got some relief from these medications,  I still remain symptomatic on day two after receiving the vaccination.
LAB_DATA: Upon awakening on the second day I remain concerned about the side effects and visited my local emergency room. The physician advised me to continue taking Benadryl. By mid day on the second day, my symptoms are still present but not quite as severe.
OTHER_MEDS: Vitamin C, vitamin D, multivitamin, Milk Thistle, Turmeric, Pro-biotic. Ibuprofen
ALLERGIES: Penicillin, Percocet, most eye makeup, almonds, shellfish

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient presented with diffuse petechiae, easy bruising and oral bruises. She has a history of stable ITP with her last required infusion of IVIG 12 years prior during pregnancy and monitors her CBC every 6 months. Her baseline platelet count is ~50-60k. She received treatment with dexamethasone 40 mg IVPB x 3 doses and IVIG 95 grams (1 gram/kg) IVPB x 2 doses.
LAB_DATA: WBC: 13.1 Hb: 13.6  HCt: 42.1 Platelets: 3 Peripheral smear: true thrombocytopenia, no clumps seen. Polychromasia, anisocytosis appreciated with some matured neutrophils. No other abnormal cells seen.
